&lt;p&gt;Since it's sorted, you can find the value closest to zero in O(log(n)) time through &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_search_algorithm" rel="nofollow"&gt;binary search&lt;/a&gt;. That value splits the array in two subarrays, one with values less than zero (call it &lt;em&gt;A&lt;/em&gt;) and one with values greater than zero (call it &lt;em&gt;B&lt;/em&gt;). Obvisouly, two values &lt;em&gt;a&lt;/em&gt; and &lt;em&gt;b&lt;/em&gt; sum up to zero if and only if &lt;em&gt;a&lt;/em&gt; = -&lt;em&gt;b&lt;/em&gt;. So you can do:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;var i = 0;
var j = 0;
while (i &amp;lt; A.length &amp;amp;&amp;amp; j &amp;lt; B.length) {
    if (A[i] == -B[j]) {
         return true;
    } else if (A[i] &amp;lt; -B[j]) {
        i++;
    } else {
        j++;
    }
}
return false;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The complexity of the algorithm above is O(n/2)=O(n), and since O(n) &amp;gt; O(log(n)) (binary search), then the overall complexity is still O(n). Note then, that you could have iterated over the array instead of using binary search and the complexity would have been the same.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;That actually makes me think you can do it all in a single loop. Just keep two pointers, one at the start of the array, one at the end, and move the progressively towards the middle. Complexity is is still O(n/2) = O(n):&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code&gt;var i = myArray.length-1;
var j = 0;
while (i &amp;gt; j) {
    if (myArray[i] == -myArray[j]) {
         return true;
    } else if (myArray[i] &amp;gt; -myArray[j]) {
        i--;
    } else {
        j++;
    }
}
return false;
&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;
